    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9457669b-9631-4096-b237-0f615f52fedf",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 51-year-old male with a stocky, slightly overweight build who presents to the outpatient clinic complaining of widespread, aching muscle pain predominantly affecting his upper back, shoulders, and thighs. He describes the pain as a persistent dull ache with occasional sharp twinges, rated 6/10 in intensity, which worsens after a long day at work or following weekend DIY projects around the house. He has noticed that the stiffness is at its worst in the morning and after prolonged sitting.\n\n{patientName} works as a warehouse logistics supervisor, spending long hours on his feet supervising floor operations and intermittently lifting and moving inventory. He is moderately active — he used to play recreational football twice a week in his 40s but has scaled back to occasional weekend walks with his dog due to increasing fatigue and muscle discomfort. He is a social beer drinker (roughly 8–10 units per week) and is a former smoker who quit 6 years ago.\n\nOutside work, {patientName} enjoys woodworking in his garage workshop, watching football, and cooking elaborate meals on Sundays. He lives with his wife and their teenage son in a semi-detached house. He is generally sociable and has a close group of friends from his football days. He admits he tends to push through pain rather than rest, and only reluctantly sought medical attention after his wife's persistent encouragement.\n\nOn examination, {patientName} appears mildly uncomfortable, shifting in his chair. There is notable tenderness to palpation over the trapezius, rhomboid, and quadriceps muscle groups bilaterally. No joint swelling or erythema is observed. His posture is slightly forward-flexed, consistent with habitual overload from his occupational activities."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:1cc7aef1-af9c-4d96-97bc-432ec9099869",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a past medical history notable for mild hypertension managed with lifestyle modifications, hypercholesterolaemia diagnosed 3 years ago (currently under dietary control without pharmacotherapy), and a prior episode of acute low back pain approximately 5 years ago that resolved with physiotherapy. He has no prior hospitalizations and no history of inflammatory arthritis, autoimmune disease, or neuromuscular disorders. He underwent a short course of physical therapy in 2019 for a rotator cuff strain sustained during a football match. His BMI is currently 27.4. {patientName} reports sleeping 5–6 hours per night due to work-related stress and occasional insomnia, which he acknowledges may be contributing to his symptoms. He does not take any regular prescribed medications, although he occasionally self-medicates with over-the-counter ibuprofen. He denies any recent viral illness, fever, rash, or weight loss."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
